{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0,0.75,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72466"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57936"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10180"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24563"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72466"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBody odour is a common physiological phenomenon that becomes noticeable during puberty. It results from the interaction between sweat gland secretions and skin bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of body odour production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chemical reaction between sebum and atmospheric oxygen","Direct secretion of volatile compounds by eccrine glands","Bacterial metabolism of apocrine gland secretions","Breakdown of dead skin cells by resident fungi","Accumulation of salt crystals on skin surface"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of body odour involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial metabolism of apocrine gland secretions\u003C/strong\u003E. Apocrine glands become active during puberty and secrete a thick, protein-rich fluid. When skin bacteria break down these secretions, they produce volatile compounds that result in characteristic body odour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemical reaction between sebum and atmospheric oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E occurs on the skin surface but does not significantly contribute to body odour production.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect secretion of volatile compounds by eccrine glands\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because eccrine sweat is primarily composed of water and electrolytes and is odourless.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakdown of dead skin cells by resident fungi\u003C/strong\u003E may occur on the skin surface but is not the primary mechanism responsible for typical body odour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of salt crystals on skin surface\u003C/strong\u003E results from evaporation of sweat but does not directly contribute to odour formation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApocrine glands are concentrated in areas where body odour is most noticeable, such as the axillae and groin. The eccrine glands, which are distributed throughout the body, produce watery sweat that functions primarily in thermoregulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Body odour primarily results from bacterial breakdown of apocrine sweat gland secretions into volatile compounds.","Apocrine sweat glands become active during puberty and are concentrated in axillae and groin regions.","Eccrine sweat glands produce odourless sweat and function in thermoregulation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57936"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57936"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:56:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:57:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10429"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72466"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id